Changed the way significance is evaluated in data w/o control.
Previously, the p-value of each ComponentFeature was being evaluated serially.
This has a result the StrandedBases of each chromosome to be evaluated as many times as the number of components.
This is prohibitive if we consider that components are on the order of hundreds of thousands.
Now, instead I gather all the components of a specific chromosome and evaluate them in groups.
So, now we have to evaluate the StrandedBases of each chromosome as many times as the number of chromosomes that correspond to the components.

I removed 2 fields which were storing too much data (actually all the data).
That is what was causing the tool to run out of memory.
Now, I'm doing it on the fly for every component. However, this will add a considerable TIME COMPLEXITY
since we will have to add a List of StrandedBases corresponding to the chromosome of a component for each condition.
Inevitable, tradeoff BETWEEN SPACE AND TIME......

***Commiting code for Giorgos***
- Added a structure AggregatedData which takes the condition-specific data and aggregates them all. It stores the results in static variables to be accessible whenever needed.

- MultiIndependentMixtureCounts.train():
After the training, I added a small piece of code where I evaluate the log-likelihood of the ALL the data. I'm doing this because I'm using it in the BindingMixture to see if the components of a region (after an update) have converged.

- MultiIndependentMixtureCounts.serial_hard_train(), .serial_soft_train() and .parallel_train():
Now I'm forcing the algorithm to start checking for convergence after it passed <tt>maxAnnealIters</tt> number of iterations. This is not principled but it has been shown to give better results. That is, better sparsity.

- MultiIndependentMixtureCounts.convergence_check():
I renamed this method and made it public so as to be accessible by other classes as well. E.g. BindingMixture.

- I added a get_glob_loglik() method.

Previously, I was giving sum_ga to prior_weight through the clone() which was really UNFORTUNATELY creating a local, temporary copy of prior_weight which was NOT passed up in the hierarchy. Now, this has been fixed.

stored the Genome and in theory the Alignment was specific to a genome,
but in many places we didn't enforce that such that a single Alignment
could be reused across Genomes.  That's hopefully fixed now.  Creating
an Alignment from an Experiment and a name now also requires a Genome.
This means you can have two alignments with the same name for the same
